## What Makes This Defensible Against DIY + Claude Code

A team with 2 engineers and a quarter of work can wire Claude Code subagents to Datadog, AWS, and Jira to pull live evidence and draft DORA packages. That is real. Here is what they still cannot get:

| Layer | Why DIY cannot replicate it |
|---|---|
| Regulator institutional knowledge | BaFin expects a specific XML schema with millisecond timestamps. AMF checks 12 specific DORA controls. This is not in any model's training data and not on the public web. It accumulates through audit cycles. |
| Audit feedback flywheel | A single customer gets one audit per regulation per year. We learn from N audits across N customers across N regulators. By year two, our mappings are sharper at no extra cost to the customer. |
| Permanent regulatory maintenance | EU regulators amend guidance constantly. DIY means owning a permanent 0.5 FTE who reads the Official Journal of the EU. We absorb this as part of the subscription. |
| Cross-regulation deduplication graph | One control evidenced once, formatted differently per regulator. A DIY team re-evidences the same control three times. |
| Auditor partnership network | Plugins ship pre-validated with named external auditors per country. DIY negotiates format with the auditor from scratch every cycle. |

